TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="SJMN91-06191081"
SELECTOR="A"
SUMMARIZER="A">

The commission that was appointed by Mayor Bradley and Police Chief
Gates to investigate the Rodney King beating by Los Angeles police was
to release its report today. According to an anonymous source the
report neither blames nor clears Chief Gates.  Gates has said he would
resign if the commission agreed with critics that he created a climate
within the police department that condoned racism and brutality. The
American Civil Liberties Union and other groups called for Gates to
resign after the March 3 incident in which white police officers
repeatedly struck King with batons, kicked him and shocked him with a
stun gun.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d06"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="WSJ910710-0148"
SELECTOR="A"
SUMMARIZER="A">

The Christopher Commission, appointed after the videotaped March 3
beating of Rodney King by Los Angeles policemen, has issued a report
that paints a picture of brutality and racism in the police
department, calls for the resignation of Chief Gates, and could prompt
changes in law enforcement nationwide. Nearly one- quarter of 650
officers responding to a commission survey agreed that "racial bias on
the part of officers toward minority citizens currently exists and
contributes to a negative interaction between police and community."
One of the commission members commented "As troubling as some of our
findings are...they are not unique to Los Angeles."</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d06"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="SJMN91-06283083"
SELECTOR="A"
SUMMARIZER="A">

The Christopher Commission's scathing report on the Los Angeles Police
Department found racism, brutality, inadequate discipline,
mismanagement and a "siege mentality" pitting officers against the
community. Now critics are calling for the same kind of independent
investigation of the sheriff's department after sheriff's deputies
shot four people dead in the space of one month, three deputies were
charged with stealing credit cards from elderly people, and there have
been renewed charges that the department is home to white supremacist
gangs. The FBI, Amnesty International and the county grand jury are
investigation allegations about both the police and sheriff's
departments.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d06"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT922-10200"
SELECTOR="A"
SUMMARIZER="A">

Ten months after the Christopher Commission called for the resignation
of Los Angeles Police Chief Daryl Gates, he has finally agreed to step
down. His decision was the result of his force's helplessness when
riots broke out after the four officers who beat Rodney King were
acquitted. Gates's departure is overdue. 

Six m nths after the Christopher Commission reported that a
significant minority of the Los Angeles police force "repetitively
misuse force," of the 44 officers identified as the object of six or
more brutality complaints, two had been fired, three had resigned and
11 removed from field duty. 28 remained untouched.</SUM>
